text: Program to facilitate the deployment of innovative or improved environmental technologies through performance
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: buyers, vendor organizations and permitters, and with the full participation of individual technology developers.  The
label: BODY

text: Filtration efficiency is computed from aerosol concentrations measured upstream and downstream of an arrestor
label: BODY

text: installed in a laboratory test rig.  The aerosol concentrations upstream and downstream of the arrestor are measured
label: BODY

text: with an aerosol analyzer that simultaneously counts and sizes the particles in the aerosol stream.  The aerosol
label: BODY

text: analyzer covers the particle diameter size range from 0.3 to 10 µm in a series of contiguous sizing channels.  Each
label: BODY

text: sizing channel covers a narrow range of particle diameters.  By taking the ratio of the downstream to upstream counts
label: BODY

text: on a channel by channel basis, the filtration efficiency is computed for each of the sizing channels.

text: Filtration efficiency was computed from aerosol concentrations measured upstream and downstream of an arrestor
label: BODY

text: installed in a laboratory test rig.  The aerosol concentrations upstream and downstream of the arrestors were
label: BODY

text: measured with an aerosol analyzer that simultaneously counts and sizes the particles in the aerosol stream.  The
label: BODY

text: aerosol analyzer covered the particle diameter size range from 0.3 to 10 µm in a series of contiguous sizing channels.
label: BODY

text: Each sizing channel covered a narrow range of particle diameters.  For example, channel 1 may cover from 0.3 to 0.4
label: BODY

text: µm, channel 2 from 0.4 to 0.5 µm, and channel 15 from 7 to 10 µm.  By taking the ratio of the downstream to
label: BODY

text: upstream counts on a channel by channel basis, the filtration efficiency was computed for each of the sizing channels.
label: BODY

text: The upstream and downstream aerosol measurements were made while a test aerosol was injected  into the air stream
label: BODY

text: upstream of the arrestor [ambient aerosol is removed with high efficiency particulate air (HEPA) filters on the inlet of
label: BODY

text: the test rig].  This test aerosol spanned the particle size range from 0.3 to 10 µm and provided a sufficient upstream
label: BODY

text: concentration in each of the sizing channels to allow accurate calculation of filtration efficiencies up to 99%.

text: DESCRIPTION OF THE TEST RIG AND METHODOLOGY
label: H4

text: The tests were conducted in RTI's air cleaner test facility (Figure A-1).  The test rig’s ducting was primarily of  24 x
label: BODY

text: 24 in.  (0.61 x 0.61m) cross section and made of 14-gauge stainless steel.  The blower is rated at 15 hp (11 kW) with
label: BODY

text: a flow capacity of 3000 cfm (1.4 m3/s) at 13 in. H2O (3200 Pa).  The inlet and outlet filter banks consist of two 24 x
label: BODY

text: 24 x 2 in. (0.61 x 0.61  x 0.05 m) prefilters and two 24 x 24 x 12 in. (0.61 x 0.61 x 0.30 m) high efficiency
label: BODY

text: particulate air (HEPA) filters rated at 2000 cfm (0.9 m3/s) each.  The system operates at positive pressure to
label: BODY

text: To mix the test aerosol with the air stream, an orifice plate and mixing baffle were located immediately downstream
label: BODY

text: of the aerosol injection point and upstream of the test arrestor.  An identical orifice plate and mixing baffle were
label: BODY

text: added after the 180° bend.  The latter downstream orifice served two purposes.  It straightened out the flow after
label: BODY

text: going around the bend, and it mixed any aerosol that penetrated the air cleaning device.  Mixing the penetrating
label: BODY

text: aerosol with the air stream is necessary to obtain a representative downstream aerosol measurement.
label: BODY

text: Airflow was measured with a 4 in. (0.1 m) ID American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) flow nozzle.  The
label: BODY

text: nominal velocity through the arrestor was computed by dividing the volumetric flow by the nominal face area of the
label: BODY

text: device.  Airflow was manually controlled by a 14 in. (0.36 m) diameter butterfly valve.
label: BODY

text: Aerosol concentrations were measured with a Climet Instruments Model 226 OPC.  This OPC uses a white-light
label: BODY

text: illumination source and has a wide collection angle for the scattered light.  The OPC's sampling rate was 0.25 cfm
label: BODY

text: The output of the OPC was input to a Climet Instruments Model 8040 multichannel analyzer equipped with Model
label: BODY

text: 05872005 and 05872006 input boards.  These boards provide 16 sizing channels covering the range from 0.3 to 10
label: BODY

text: µm.  The 8040 was also equipped with a Model CI-298 sequential interface board.  This interface provides a contact
label: BODY

text: closure at the end of each sample and also provides a 15-sec delay in particle counting after each sample.  The
label: BODY

text: contact closure was used to control the operation of electromechanical valve actuators in the upstream and
label: BODY

text: downstream sample lines.  The 15-sec delay allows time for the new sample to be acquired.
label: BODY

text: Figure A-1.  Schematic illustration of the fractional efficiency test rig.
label: BODY

text: Two types of challenge aerosols were used:  liquid- and solid-phase.  The selection of liquid- or solid-phase challenge
label: BODY

text: aerosol particles is important because for some types of paint arrestors significantly different filtration efficiencies
label: BODY

text: will be achieved depending upon the phase of the challenge aerosol particles.  (This is due to particle "bounce"
label: BODY

text: associated with solid-phase particles.) The liquid-phase challenge aerosol is oleic acid, a non-toxic, low-volatility
label: BODY

text: liquid.  The solid-phase aerosol is potassium chloride (KCl) generated from an aqueous solution.  KCl was selected as
label: BODY

text: the solid-phase aerosol because of its relatively high water solubility, high deliquescence humidity (85% relative
label: BODY

text: humidity), known crystalline structure (facilitates complete drying), and low toxicity.  The KCl solution was prepared
label: BODY

text: by combining 0.66 lb (300 g ) of KCl with 0.035 ft3 (1 L) of distilled water.  Both oleic acid and KCl are compatible
label: BODY

text: with accurate measurement by the optical particle counter.
label: BODY

text: The oleic acid or the KCl solution was nebulized using a two-fluid (air and liquid) air atomizing nozzle (Spray
label: BODY

text: Systems 1/4 J siphon spray nozzle) as illustrated in Figure A-1 (aerosol generation system).  The nozzle was
label: BODY

text: positioned at the top of a 12 in. (0.30 m) diameter, 51 in. (1.3 m) tall transparent acrylic spray tower.  The tower
label: BODY

text: served two purposes.  It allowed the salt droplets to dry by providing an approximate 40 sec. mean residence time,
label: BODY
